Here's the proper approach using MAUI's app lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Restore draft on page load
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Resumed += OnResumed;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Backgrounding += OnBackgrounding;
    }

    private void OnBackgrounding(object sender, BackgroundingEventArgs e)
    {
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void OnResumed(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    // Clean up when user explicitly saves/discards
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }

    ~NotePage()
    {
        App.Current.Windows[0].Resumed -= OnResumed;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Backgrounding -= OnBackgrounding;
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Backgrounding`** fires when the app moves to the background — save here.
- **`Resumed`** fires when the app returns — restore here.
- **`Preferences`** is a simple key-value store that persists across sessions (backed by `SharedPreferences` on Android, `NSUserDefaults` on iOS).
- Call `ClearDraft()` when the user explicitly saves or discards the note so stale drafts don't linger.
- Unsubscribe from events to avoid leaks.

For larger drafts, consider `SecureStorage` or writing to a file via `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` instead of `Preferences`.
